Problem 1¶

Prove that any projection matrix $P$ for an orthogonal projection in $\mathbb{R}^n$ satisfies the two properties:

(a) $P^2 = P$

(b) $P$ is symmetric

Solution¶

(a) By definition, for any $x \in \mathbb{R}^n$

$$\begin{align*} P\left(Px\right) &= Px\\ P^2x &= Px\\ \left(P^2 - P\right)x &= 0 \end{align*}$$

(b)

By definition, for any $x, y \in \mathbb{R}^n$

$$\left(Px - Py\right) \perp \left(y-Py\right)$$

Consequently,

$$0 = \left(Px - Py\right)^T\left(y-Py\right) = \left(x-y\right)^Tp^T\left(I-P\right)y = \left(x-y\right)^T\left(P^T-P^TP\right)y=0$$

for any $x, y \in \mathbb{R}^n$. This shows that $P^T = P^TP$. Then, $P = \left(P^T\right)^T = \left(P^TP\right)^T = P^TP = P^T$

Problem 2¶

Show that the hyperplane $g(X) = \omega^TX + b = 0$ is perpendicular to $\omega$.

Solution¶

If $X_1$ and $X_2$ are any points on the hyperplane, then the followings are satisfied:


$$\begin{align*} g(X_1) = \omega^TX_1 + b = 0\\ g(X_2) = \omega^TX_2 + b = 0 \end{align*} $$

We can show that

$$g(X_1) - g(X_2) = \omega^TX_1 - \omega^TX_2 = \omega^T(X_1 - X_2) = 0 \implies \omega \perp (X_1 - X_2)$$

Problem 3¶

Let $x$ be a block vector with two vector elements, $x = \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\end{bmatrix}$ where $a$ and $b$ are vectors of size $n$ and $m$, respectively. Show that


$$\lVert x \rVert = \left(\lVert a \rVert^2 + \lVert b \rVert^2 \right)^{\frac{1}{2}} = \left\lVert \begin{bmatrix} \lVert a \rVert \\ \lVert b \rVert \end{bmatrix} \right\rVert$$


(Note that the norm on the right-hand side is of a 2-vector)

Solution¶

$$\begin{align*} \lVert x \rVert^2 &= \lVert a \rVert^2 + \lVert b \rVert^2\\ \\ \lVert a \rVert^2 + \lVert b \rVert^2 &= \left \lVert \begin{bmatrix} \lVert a \rVert \\ \lVert b \rVert \end{bmatrix} \right \rVert^2 \end{align*}$$

Problem 4¶

Represent each of the following three functions $f: \mathbb{R}^2 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^2$ as a matrix-vector product $f(x) = Ax$

(a) $f(x)$ is obtained by reflecting $x$ about the $x_1$ axis

(b) $f(x)$ is $x$ reflected about the $x_1$ axis, followed by a counter clockwise rotation of 30 degrees.

(c) $f(x)$ is $x$ rotated counterclockwise over 30 degrees, followed by a reflection about the $x_1$ axis

Solution¶

(a)

$$f(x) = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{bmatrix}x$$

(b)

$$\begin{align*} R(\theta) &: \text{ rotation matrix }\\ f(x) &= R\left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right)\begin{bmatrix}1&0\\0&-1\end{bmatrix} \end{align*}$$

(c)

$$f(x) = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{bmatrix}R\left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right)$$

Problem 5¶

Fibonacci sequence is defined as the follwing:


$$F_{k+2} = F_{k+1} + F_{k} \qquad \text{with} \;F_0 = 0, \;F_1 = 1$$


It is known that the ratio of $F_{k+1}$ to $F_{k}$ is close to 'golden mean'. That is,


$$\lim_{k \to \infty} \frac{F_{k+1}}{F_{k}} = \frac{\left(1 + \sqrt{5}\right)}{2}$$


Show the above equation using eigenvectors and eigenvalues.

Solution¶

$ F_{k+2} = F_{k+1}+F_k$ is the second oreder linear system


$$ \begin{bmatrix} F_{k+2} \\ F_{k+1} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} F_{k+1} \\ F_{k} \end{bmatrix} $$

$ \text{Eigen Anlaysis} $

$$ \text{det}(A-\lambda I) =0 $$$$ \lambda_1 ,\ \lambda_2 = \frac{1\pm \sqrt5}{2} $$

$X_1)$ $$ \begin{align} & \begin{bmatrix} 1-\frac{1 + \sqrt5}{2} & 1 \\ 1 & -\frac{1 + \sqrt5}{2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \\[0.01em] X_1 \\ \\[0.01em] \end{bmatrix} \\ \\ \implies & \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1 - \sqrt5}{2} & 1 \\ 1 & \frac{-1 - \sqrt5}{2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1 + \sqrt5}{2} \\[0.6em] 1 \end{bmatrix} = 0 \\ \end{align} $$

$\text{So,}$

$$ X_1 = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1 + \sqrt5}{2} \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} $$

$X_2$) Replacing $\sqrt5 \rightarrow -\sqrt5 $ to the previous result gives

$$ X_2 = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1 - \sqrt5}{2} \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \\ \\ $$


$$ \begin{align} \text{So,} \quad \begin{bmatrix} F_{n+1} \\ F_{n} \end{bmatrix} & = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{bmatrix}^n \begin{bmatrix} F_1 \\ F_0 \end{bmatrix} \\ \\ & = C_1\left(\frac{1 + \sqrt5}{2}\right)^n x_1 + C_2 \left(\frac{1 - \sqrt5}{2}\right)^n x_2 \\ \\ \text{Then,} \quad \lim\limits_{n \to \infty} \frac{F_{n+1}}{F_{n}} & = \lim\limits_{n \to \infty} \frac{C_1\left(\frac{1 + \sqrt5}{2}\right)^{n+1} }{C_1\left(\frac{1 + \sqrt5}{2}\right)^n } \\ \\ & = \frac{1 + \sqrt5}{2} \\ \\ \end{align} $$

$$ \left(* \lim\limits_{n \to \infty} \left(\frac{1 - \sqrt5}{2}\right)^n = 0 \quad \text{since, } \left\lvert\frac{1 - \sqrt5}{2}\right\rvert < 1 \right) $$

Problem 6¶

(a) Find the solution using the derivatives of the following objective function:


$$\min_{x} \,\,\, (2x_1 - 1)^2 + (-x_1 + x_2)^2 + (2x_2 +1)^2$$


(b) Formulate the above corresponding least-squares problem (i.e., find one of possible $A$ and $b$), and solve it using cvxpy.


$$\min_{x} \, \lVert Ax - b\rVert_2 ^2$$


(c) How many suboptimal points exist? Why?

Solution¶

(a)

Let

$$ \begin{align*} f &= (2x_1 - 1)^2 + (-x_1 + x_2)^2 + (2x_2 +1)^2 \\ \\ \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_1} &= 2(2x_1 - 1)2 + (-x_1 + x_2)(-1) = 10x_1 - 2x_2 - 4 = 0 \\ \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_2} &= 2(-x_1 + x_2) + 2(2x_2 + 1)2 = -2x_1 + 10x_2 + 4 = 0 \\ \end{align*} $$


Matrix form

$$ \begin{bmatrix} 10 & -2 \\ -2 & 10 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} -4 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = 0 $$

So, $$ \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 10 & -2 \\ -2 & -10 \end{bmatrix}^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} -4 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{96}\begin{bmatrix} 10 & 2 \\ 2 & 10 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} -4 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} =\frac{1}{3}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} $$

Thus $$ x_1 = \frac{1}{3} \quad \text{and}\quad x_2 = -\frac{1}{3} $$

(b)

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import cvxpy as cvx

x = cvx.Variable(2, 1)
A = np.array([[2, 0], [-1, 1], [0, 2]])
b = np.array([[1], [0], [-1]])
objective = cvx.Minimize(cvx.norm(A*x - b, 2))
prob = cvx.Problem(objective)
result = prob.solve()

print(x.value)
print(result**2)

[[ 0.33333333]
 [-0.33333333]]
0.6666666662110364

(c)

Zero (or one global optimum). This function has no subpotimal point since it is convex. We need to probe the function is a convex function


$$ \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_1} =2(2x_1 - 1)2 + (-x_1 + x_2)(-1) = \ 10x_1 - 2x_2 - 4 = 0 $$$$ \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_2} =2(-x_1 + x_2) + 2(2x_2 + 1)2 = \ -2x_1 + 10x_2 + 4 = 0 $$



$$ \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_1^2} =2\cdot2\cdot2 + 2 = 10 \qquad \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_1\partial x_2} = -2 $$

$$ \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_2^2} =2 + 2\cdot2\cdot2 = 10 \qquad \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_1\partial x_2} = -2 $$

$f(x) = \mathbb{R}^2\to\mathbb{R}$ & it is twice differentiable over an open domain.

Then,

$$ \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x^2}= \begin{bmatrix}\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_1^2}& \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_1\partial x_2} \\ \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_1\partial x_2}& \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_2^2} \end{bmatrix}= \begin{bmatrix}10&-2 \\ -2&10 \end{bmatrix}\ $$


Use Hessian determinant

$$\det \left(\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x^2} \right)= 100 - 4 = 96 \geq 0 \quad \text{for all }x \in \text{domain}(f(x))$$

Thus, $f(x)$ is a convex function

3) Perspective homography for image 1 and image 2¶

In [18]:
Phi01 = []
newpos01 = []
for i in range(8):
    temp1 = [[pos1[0,i], pos1[1,i], 1, 0, 0, 0, -pos2[0,i]*pos1[0,i], -pos2[0,i]*pos1[1,i]],
            [0, 0, 0, pos1[0,i], pos1[1,i], 1, -pos2[1,i]*pos1[0,i], -pos2[1,i]*pos1[1,i]]]
    temp2 = [[pos2[0,i]], [pos2[1,i]]]
    Phi01.append(temp1)
    newpos01.append(temp2)

Phi01 = np.concatenate(Phi01, axis=0)
newpos01 = np.concatenate(newpos01, axis=0).reshape(-1, 1)
Phi01 = np.asmatrix(Phi01)
newpos01 = np.asarray(newpos01)

perspective_theta = (Phi01.T*Phi01).I*Phi01.T*newpos01
perspective_theta = np.vstack([perspective_theta, [1]])
perspective_theta = perspective_theta.reshape(3, 3)
